06900nam a22010335i 9781400843879DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20212003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008438797 a10.1515/97814008438792doi  a(DE-B1597)572668  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0100102bisacsh1 aKenney, Padraic, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Carnival of Revolution :bCentral Europe 1989 /cPadraic Kenney. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b22 halftones. 4 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tINTRODUCTION Street Theater, Concrete Poetry -- tPART ONE: ACTORS, STAGES, REPERTOIRES -- tCHAPTER ONE Eating the Crocodile with a Spoon, or, A Career Guide to the Underground -- tCHAPTER TWO Come With Us! They Aren't Beating Today! The Art of the Blizzard -- tCHAPTER THREE As If in Europe: The International World of Peace and Human Rights -- tCHAPTER FOUR The New Politics of the Konkretny Generation -- tCHAPTER FIVE How the Smurfs Captured Gargamel, or, A Revolution of Style -- tPHOTOESSAY: PHOTOGRAPHING THE CARNIVAL -- tPART TWO: A REVOLUTION IN SIXTEEN SCENES -- tSCENE ONE: "I Blink, and I See Another World": The Candlelight March -- tSCENE TWO: A Tale of Two Lenins -- tSCENE THREE: Slovene Spring -- tSCENE FOUR: Days That Shook Lviv -- tSCENE FIVE: Strikes in Shades of Orange -- tSCENE SIX: An Invasion Remembered -- tSCENE SEVEN: WaterDam/ned: Hungary Defends the Danube -- tSCENE EIGHT: Independence Day and Palach Week -- tSCENE NINE: Encircling the Round Table -- tSCENE TEN: Mothers and Children -- tSCENE ELEVEN: On the Fourth of June -- tSCENE TWELVE: Hungarians Bury the Communists -- tSCENE THIRTEEN: Korzos and Road Races -- tSCENE FOURTEEN: Lviv Passes the Baton -- tSCENE FIFTEEN: The Mosquito and the Messedemos -- tSCENE SIXTEEN: Bring a Flower with You! The Velvet Revolution -- tEPILOGUE No More Picnics, After the Revolution -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNotes -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first history of the revolutions that toppled communism in Europe to look behind the scenes at the grassroots movements that made those revolutions happen. It looks for answers not in the salons of power brokers and famed intellectuals, not in decrepit economies--but in the whirlwind of activity that stirred so crucially, unstoppably, on the street. Melding his experience in Solidarity-era Poland with the sensibility of a historian, Padraic Kenney takes us into the hearts and minds of those revolutionaries across much of Central Europe who have since faded namelessly back into everyday life. This is a riveting story of musicians, artists, and guerrilla theater collectives subverting traditions and state power; a story of youthful social movements emerging in the 1980s in Poland, East Germany, Czechoslovakia, Hungary, and parts of Yugoslavia and the Soviet Union.Kenney argues that these movements were active well before glasnost. Some protested military or environmental policy. Others sought to revive national traditions or to help those at the margins of society. Many crossed forbidden borders to meet their counterparts in neighboring countries. They all conquered fear and apathy to bring people out into the streets. The result was a revolution unlike any other before: nonviolent, exuberant, even light-hearted, but also with a relentless political focus--a revolution that leapt from country to country in the exciting events of 1988 and 1989.A Carnival of Revolution resounds with the atmosphere of those turbulent years: the daring of new movements, the unpredictability of street demonstrations, and the hopes and regrets of the young participants. A vivid photo-essay complements engaging prose to fully capture the drama. Based on over two hundred interviews in twelve countries, and drawing on samizdat and other writings in six languages, this is among the most insightful and compelling accounts ever published of the historical milestone that ushered in our age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aAfghanistan.  aAustria.  aBaltic republics.  aBerlin.  aBratislava.  aBudapest.  aCeausescu, Nicolae.  aCharter.  aCivic Forum.  aCzaputowicz, Jacek.  aCzęstochowa.  aDanube River.  aDrakulic, Slavenka.  aEsche, Dieter.  aFighting Solidarity.  aFrasyniuk, Władysław.  aGandhi, Mahatma.  aGorbachev, Mikhail.  aHavel, Václav.  aHelsinki Accords.  aHelsinki Memorandum.  aHren, Marko.  aIndependent Peace Association (NMS).  aInternational Human Rights Conference.  aJakubczak, Krzysztof.  aJaruzelski, Wojciech.  aJohn Lennon Peace Club.  aKalynets, Iryna.  aKeszthelyi, Zsolt.  aKuroń, Jacek.  aLion Society.  aNiemczyk, Piotr.  aanarchists and anarchism.  amartial law (Poland).  amusic and Opposition.  apluralism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400843879zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400843879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400843879.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK